SIMPLE: imperial
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Imperial
<hw>Im*pe"ri*al</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>emperial</ets>, OF. <ets>emperial</ets>, F.
<ets>imp⟦eacute⟧rial</ets>, fr. L. <ets>imperialis</ets>, fr.
<ets>imperium</ets> command, sovereignty, empire. See
<er>Empire</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Of or pertaining to an empire,
or to an emperor; <as>as, an <ex>imperial</ex> government;
<ex>imperial</ex> authority or edict.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The last⟦br⟧
That wore the <qex>imperial</qex> diadem of Rome.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Belonging to, or suitable to, supreme authority, or
one who wields it; royal; sovereign; supreme.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧The
<xex>imperial</xex> democracy of Athens.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Mitford.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Who, as Ulysses says, opinion crowns⟦br⟧
With an <qex>imperial</qex> voice.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To tame the proud, the fetter'd slave to free,⟦br⟧
These are <qex>imperial</qex> arts, and worthy thee.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He sounds his <qex>imperial</qex> clarion along the whole line of
battle.</q> <rj><qau>E. Everett.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Of superior or unusual size or excellence; <as>as,
<ex>imperial</ex> paper; <ex>imperial</ex> tea, etc.</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Imperial bushel</b></col>,
<col><b>gallon</b></col></mcol>, <cd>etc. See <er>Bushel</er>,
<er>Gallon</er>, etc.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial chamber</b></col>,
<cd>the, the sovereign court of the old German empire.</cd> --
<col><b>Imperial city</b></col>, <cd>under the first German empire, a
city having no head but the emperor.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial
diet</b></col>, <cd>an assembly of all the states of the German
empire.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial drill</b></col>. <fld>(Manuf.)</fld>
<cd>See under 8th <er>Drill</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial
eagle</b></col>. <fld>(Zool.)</fld> <cd>See <er>Eagle</er>.</cd> --
<col><b>Imperial green</b></col>. <cd>See <cref>Paris green</cref>,
under <er>Green</er>.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial guard</b></col>, <cd>the
royal guard instituted by Napoleon I.</cd> -- <col><b>Imperial weights
and measures</b></col>, <cd>the standards legalized by the British
Parliament.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperial</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Imperial
<hw>Im*pe"ri*al</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F.
<ets>imp⟦eacute⟧riale</ets>: cf. Sp. <ets>imperial</ets>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>The tuft of hair on a man's lower lip and chin; --
so called from the style of beard of Napoleon III.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>An outside seat on a diligence.</def> <rj><au>T.
Hughes.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>A luggage case on the top of a coach.</def>
<rj><au>Simmonds.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Anything of unusual size or excellence, as a large
decanter, a kind of large photograph, a large sheet of drawing,
printing, or writing paper, etc.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>A gold coin of Russia worth ten rubles, or about
eight dollars.</def> <rj><au>McElrath.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>6.</sn> <def>A kind of fine cloth brought into England from
Greece. or other Eastern countries, in the Middle Ages.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>7.</sn> <def>A game at cards differing from piquet in some minor
details, and in having a trump; also, any one of several combinations of
cards which score in this game.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Imperialism</ent>⟦br⟧
